Sorry, let me try and explain it a bit clearer. 

I'm using filesaver.js to download a container of user-defined and predefined information on an intranet setup. When the user enters this specific page they are prompted with 5 or 6 input fields asking for information. As they fill out the input fields requesting information from the user a div container to the right dynamically updates with their input field updates placing them in the proper order with other predefined information (images, addresses, etc.)

Once the user has completed the input fields they click a button that preps the downloadable HTML file containing the div container and then replaces the prep button with a Save button that downloads the HTML file for us. 

Up to this point, everything works wonderfully. 

My question is I noticed that some people were leaving key input fields blank such as name and contact. I would like to make those required. Normally I'd just add "required" to an input field to do so, however, with FileSaver.js since it's not submitting anything in a traditional sense, it doesn't register those required options before prepping and saving out the file. 

My thought was to wrap the hook calling out the prep and save with the following code idea thinking I could force it to confirm any input not filled out with class would first prompt an alert box before allowing the prep and download: 

if($('input.required') === "" || $('input.required') === "placeholder"){
     // console alert box prompted
}else{
     // proceed with prepare and save.
}

But so far I've had no success in doing so and was hoping to get some thoughts.

