You can still use the manifest syntax at the beginning of an .scss file. We have a production app that uses to import libraries - from that `application.scss`:
```sass
/*
 *= require xyz
 *= require_self
*/

@import "bootstrap";
```

using a `bootstrap_and_overrides` file and Sprockets `require_tree` is not recommended, since you will be unable to use Bootstrap variables in your Sass files within that tree.

Sadly the manual doesn't really talk about the nitty-gritty of this in much detail.  Conceptually `$x` where `x` is a string seems to be rather like `with` in Pascal - it gives an implied context to a group of operations.  But it's unclear from the manual if it's a lexical group or if this implied context needs to be carried into subroutines (currently it is for C, and that's probably more sensible, though perhaps harder to implement for some backends).

> What about integer and boolean variables?

In C those aren't restored - here's `struct SN_env`'s definition:

```
struct SN_env {
    symbol * p;
    int c; int l; int lb; int bra; int ket;
    symbol * * S;
    int * I;
    unsigned char * B;
};
```

The shallow copies which happen before and after the group of operations will (needlessly) copy the pointers `S`, `I`, and `B`, but those pointers don't ever change during execution of the snowball program so that won't change any of the snowball variables.  The part which is important is that struct members `p` to `ket` are copied and restored.  We could optimise this slightly to just copy the start of the struct (on x86-84 we'd copy 28 instead of 56 bytes; on x86, 24 instead of 36 bytes).

So for Java a correct implementation would be approximately:

```
SnowballProgram v_1 = new SnowballProgram();
v_1.copy_from((SnowballProgram) this);
current = S_x;

// ...

((SnowballProgram) this).copy_from(v_1);
```

This relies on the fact that Java object variables are really references, so after `current = S_x;` modifying `current` also modifies `S_x`.

Except that in the Java backend `current` is a `StringBuffer` and `S_x` a `StringBuilder` (or compatible class the user specifies) so you can't just assign them like this, and also I'm not sure quite how this is meant to interact with the failure mechanism.

